article.description: Brian Cook scored five straight points during a key stretch of the second half to rescue the sluggish 15th-ranked Fighting Illini with a 73-61 victory.
article.headline: Illini edge Wildcats for seventh straight time
article.linkText: Powell's career outing leads Illinois past Northwestern
article.story: CHICAGO (AP) -- Roger Powell carried Illinois early and Brian Cook took over when it mattered most. And Northwestern never found an answer for either. Powell had a career-high 20 points and Cook scored 13 of his 17 in the second half as (No. 15 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP) Illinois beat the Wildcats 73-61 on Saturday. Cook got off to a slow start but made up for it during a crucial stretch in the second half. After going just 1-of-3 from the field in the first half, the senior scored 10 of 12 points, including an alley-oop dunk, for the Illini (18-5, 8-4 Big Ten) over an eight-minute span to help extend their lead back to nine with 3:30 to go. "I just felt in the last minutes that I can kind of take over,'' Cook said. "My shot started to fall and I was starting to get good position down low.'' Cook, the Big Ten's leading scorer at 19.8 points a game, scored the Illini's first basket of second half. He then called for the ball each time down the court after Northwestern cut the Illini lead to six with 10:23 to play. Cook finished 6-of-11 from the field and had 10 rebounds as Illinois defeated Northwestern for the seventh consecutive time and improved to 33-3 against the Wildcats (10-14, 2-11) dating to 1984. "He played much better in the second half,'' Illinois coach Bill Self said of Cook. "Brian had an off first half. I think he just played much better, more aggressive.'' Powell was starting his second straight game after coming off the bench the last 10 games while recovering from a toe injury. The sophomore scored 11 points during a 22-6 run as the Illini opened a 31-13 lead. Powell also hit two 3s, tying a career high, and surprised Jitim Young from behind by blocking his attempted dunk on a breakaway. After playing sparingly for a month because of his injured toe, Powell has put together consecutive solid games. He had 10 points, seven rebounds and played a season-high 30 minutes in a win over Michigan State on Tuesday. "When he's slashing in there, getting layups, dunking on folks, he adds another dimension to our team,'' Cook said. "We'll need that over the home stretch.'' Dee Brown had 18 points, five rebounds, five assists and five steals for Illinois. Illinois shot 74 percent in the first half but saw its 18-point lead trimmed to 43-33 at halftime. Mohamed Hachad hit two 3-pointers and scored eight straight points for Northwestern during a 10-2 run that got it back into the game before the half. This was the second time in as many games Northwestern has fallen behind big only to make a late run and come up short. The Wildcats were down by 26 against Minnesota in the second half, cut the deficit to five before losing 73-61. "They came up with the big plays when they had to. It's disappointing, but I certainly liked the way our guys played to tell you the truth. We played hard,'' Northwestern coach Bill Carmody said. Jason Burke led the Wildcats with 15 points on 6-of-8 shooting, while Aaron Jennings and T.J. Parker each had 13. Illinois was playing without Luther Head, who has been battling a nagging groin injury that has kept him out of six games this season. Self got his 200th win in a matchup that felt like a home game for the Illini despite being at the United Center in Chicago. Self has never lost to Northwestern. Self said compared to Texas Tech coach Bob Knight's 800 wins, 200 didn't seem like much of an accomplishment. Still, after a 6-21 season his first year coaching Oral Roberts, Self said he wasn't taking the milestone for granted. "I know the way I started, if we would have projected it would have taken about 45 years to get to 200,'' he said.
